<div class='bookAuthorProfile__about'>

<span id="freeTextContainer13456895808777673561">Imaam Abul-Husain Muslim ibn-ul-Hajjaaj al-Qushairee an-Naisaabooree<br/><br/>One of the chief authorities on the Hadeeth. Muslim traveled widely; his great work, <i>Al-Musnad-us-Saheeh</i>, is said to have been compiled from about 300,000 hadeeths, which he collected in Arabia, Egypt, Syria, and Iraq. The <i>Saheeh</i> has been unanimously acclaimed as authoritative and is one of the two canonical compilations of Hadeet</span>
  <span id="freeText13456895808777673561" style="display:none">Imaam Abul-Husain Muslim ibn-ul-Hajjaaj al-Qushairee an-Naisaabooree<br /><br />One of the chief authorities on the Hadeeth. Muslim traveled widely; his great work, <i>Al-Musnad-us-Saheeh</i>, is said to have been compiled from about 300,000 hadeeths, which he collected in Arabia, Egypt, Syria, and Iraq. The <i>Saheeh</i> has been unanimously acclaimed as authoritative and is one of the two canonical compilations of Hadeeth, along with the book of his teacher, Imaam al-Bukhaaree. <br /><br />Muslim was careful to give a full account of the <i>isnaads</i> (chains of transmission) for each hadeeth and to record textual variations. The collection also includes an introduction discussing Hadeeth Science.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13456895808777673561" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

</div>
